I had a moment at @sweeneytoddbway rehearsal the other day where I flashed back to myself as a 15-year-old playing “Kiss Me” at home, for no one else and for no other reason than the sheer joy of playing a challenging piano part for a lovely song. It would have been BLISS to accompany folks on it back in 1990. 33 years later, I get the opportunity to play it with amazing singers such as these two, and I get to do it on a regular basis. I felt compelled to take a picture to remind me of the moment where young and old Lac intersected. Living the dream, y’all…

I’m still reeling from this weekend’s sitzprobe.
I had moments of holding back tears, for it would hit me that I was conducting SWEENEY TODD for the first time in my life.
There were also other moments when those tears would flow freely, for it would hit me that I have the *honor* of conducting SWEENEY TODD.
The level of musicianship in the room is astounding.
Having Jonathan Tunick’s input has been invaluable to the process.
It was an emotional day, one that I’ll remember for the rest of my life.
Thank you to everyone who made Saturday such a glorious experience — looking forward to what’s next. 
Eternal thanks to Stephen Sondheim, who left us this masterpiece that we‘ll soon have the pleasure of performing for all of you. 
❤️🎶
📸: @your_gal_dal and @raymondjlee!
@sweeneytoddbway

IN THE HEIGHTS opened on Broadway 15 years ago today. 
With each moment of the process, I made a point of saying to myself: “Remember this experience and cherish it, for a show like this doesn’t come around often.”
When I think back on HEIGHTS, everything I see in my memory banks brings me joy. It’s images of laughter, of creative inspiration, and lasting community. Familia. It warms my heart to hear how many other productions of HEIGHTS have sparked that same sense of joy and belonging to those lucky enough to take part. 
Eternally grateful for Lin, Q, TK, Blank, Sherm, and every single person on our journey who changed my life for the best. 

📸: @bruglikas @joshlehrerphotography @mickeythek @alacamoire

This is my personal copy of the score to SWEENEY TODD. Mom bought it for me in 1990. It cost $75 at a time when my family could hardly afford such an extravagant purchase. Mom asked “Are you SURE you want this?” To own it felt like a “need” more than a “want.” I NEEDED to play those accompaniments. I HAD to see the notes on the page, because the music affected me so deeply that it became IMPERATIVE to understand how it all worked. 
Today I have the privilege of opening this revival of my favorite show. I have the honor of conducting a marvelous orchestra under a magnificent cast, all of us brought together by dear colleagues and friends. 
Life is but a dream, y’all.
Thank you, Stephen Sondheim. My 15-year-old self can’t comprehend this good fortune. 
Congrats to everyone involved with EVERY PRODUCTION of SWEENEY — we are here because of you. 
And thank you, Mama Lac, for splurging on that book for your son. 
Happy Opening, fam!
@sweeneytoddbway

Conducting @sweeneytoddbway has been a DREAM. I never thought I’d get the opportunity to wave a baton through this masterpiece of a score but, boy, am I glad I did. Being on the podium for this one challenged me out of my comfort zone, and I’m EVER grateful to those who believed I could do this, even when I didn’t believe it myself. Thank you, @kristenblodgette, thank you. s/o to Salvatore Di Vittorio for guiding me to a better stick technique! 
To Stephen Sondheim, whose genius BLAZES in every note of this score — thank you for gracing us with this gift that has changed all our lives. ❤️

My gift to Ileana for her 50th birthday was a park bench in her name. It’s in Fort Washington Park, home to the Little Red Lighthouse, in the neighborhood where she was raised. 

Growing up on 180th and Cabrini in Washington Heights, Ileana had a view of the George Washington Bridge all her life. When my mother-in-law passed last year, Ileana lost not only her mom but her childhood apartment as well. I wanted to ensure that Ileana would always have a place in the old ‘hood that was “hers,” with a view of that great grey bridge and the river it crosses. 

This past Sunday, Ileana got to see her bench and plaque in person for the first time. 

Happy 50th Birthday, sweetheart. This is your city, your neighborhood, and your home. 

❤️,

Alex

My time with WICKED was during some of the most formative years of my life. I was 28 when we opened. I had only just moved to NYC, and here I was working with a composer I’d long admired. It was my first Broadway credit as an arranger, my first time conducting a Broadway pit, and eventually my first stint as Music Director on Broadway. It’s where I gained the most confidence in my career, and where I forged l relationships that fuel me to this day. My gratitude is overflowing on this milestone birthday for our show. 💚
Happy 20th WICKED, and thank you to Stephen Schwartz, @steoremus, and Marc Platt for bringing me on board.

It’s #GivingTuesday, everyone! I’m excited to support Broadway Cares Equity Fights Aids (@bcefa), an organization I’ve been a fan of for years, to help those in need this holiday season. I’ve set a goal to provide 100 meals and I encourage you to support if you can. What’s more: any donations made will be matched up to $100,000 by @citynationalbank!

Let’s aim to make this an awesome Giving Tuesday, all.

Donation link in my bio!

Join me in the #GivingTuesday movement to help MUSE! At @museonline_org, our goal of raising $10,000 would help us hire more staff, enhance our programming, and host in-person events, all in pursuit of racial equity within the Music Departments of theater spaces. MUSE is all about providing access for historically marginalized People Of Color, and as a Cuban-American, this mission is close to my heart. Any donation to support MUSE is greatly appreciated! Click the link in my bio to support MUSE and to make a difference. Thanks, everyone! 🎶♥️
